apply spec-kit extension: to generate a file test-plan.md which includes unit tests and integration tests which later can be run in deployment pipeline in OpenShift
https://github.com/firstlast20200202/spec-kit/blob/main/extensions/EXTENSION-DEVELOPMENT-GUIDE.md
if commit in VScode UI takes forever, just open Terminal in it:
git add .
git commit -m "blabla"

extension structure：
.specify/
└── extensions/
    └── my-ext/
        ├── manifest.yml           //important
        ├── my-ext-config.yml
        ├── templates/
        └── commands/
            └── testplan.md

my-ext-config.yml is optional, in reality the structure would be:
.specify/extensions/my-ext/
        ├── extension.yml           
        ├── templates/
        └── commands/

a hook is a mechanism that lets software automatically run some additional logic when a specifc event occurs.
a complementary extension is an extension that works alongside another extension or the core SpecKit workflow. （是对其它extension或者core SpecKit workflow的一个补充）


Extension Configuration:
step 5:
$ cd <my-project>
$ specify extension add --dev ../spec-kit-practice/my-extension

Manifest Schema Reference section is telling how to write manifest,yml; Command File Format section is telling how to write testplan.md
manifest: tells the system what commands we have; command file: tells the system how to execute the commands


Configuration Files：to seperate configuration from application behaviours

.extensionignore files: similar to .gitignore, specify which files are not included in the extension package which would be sent to users for installation
eg. 
my-ext/
├── manifest.yml
├── commands/
├── templates/
├── README.md
├── .git/
├── .vscode/
├── test/
├── logs/
└── .extensionignore

commands/ ✅ 
manifest.yml ✅ 
templates/ ✅ 
other files would be NOT sent to users


